Nonetheless, not all shorebirds are declining and there may be differences among species and populations using different migratory routes. For instance, previous meta-analyses have suggested that shorebirds using the Mid-Continental Flyway are experiencing more rapid declines than those using the Pacific or Atlantic flyways (Thomas et al. 2006). At the same time, within a species, more northerly breeding populations are experiencing greater phenological mismatches and lower reproductive success than southerly ones (Kwon et al. 2019). What remains unclear, however, are the underlying causes of these intra- and inter-specific differences, which limits our ability to focus conservation efforts where they are needed most. Two aspects of shorebird migratory ecology that may contribute to inter- and intra-specific differences in population dynamics have been generally overlooked: their phenology and their stopover site usage during fall migration. Deepening our understanding of fall migration will help provide a full annual cycle perspective (e.g., Marra et al. 2015) for shorebirds and highlight how anthropogenic change may be influencing the ability of individuals and populations to dissipate the enormous energetic costs associated with migration and reproduction (Senner et al. 2015). Such insights can then be used to target specific sites and portions of species annual cycles that are most in need of targeted conservation and management actions. In the face of rapidly warming global temperatures, the phenology of spring migration has rightly received considerable attention. This attention has elucidated the cues that shorebirds use to time their spring migrations (Senner 2012, Lamarre et al. 2021), the mechanisms enabling individuals to track changes in their environments (Gill et al. 2013, Conklin et al. 2021), and the consequences for those species that are incapable of breeding sufficiently early (Senner et al. 2017, Saalfeld et al. 2019, Ruthrauff et al. 2021). Relatively little attention, however, has been paid to similar questions about fall migration. Thus, while we know that such factors as predator abundance and migratory phenology can influence when and where shorebirds migrate (Lank et al. 2003, Ydenberg et al. 2004), we do not yet know what role anthropogenic change may be playing in such processes. For instance, if spring migration must get progressively earlier to keep pace with warming spring temperatures but fall migration does not also shift earlier, individuals may soon be faced with a situation in which they do not have sufficient time to recover from the breeding season and migration, molt, and prepare for northward migration (Conklin and Battley 2012, Senner et al. 2014). As a result, generating insights into the drivers of fall migration timing could provide an avenue to facilitate earlier spring migrations as well. Identifying the network of stopover sites used by migratory shorebirds has similarly, and rightly, received substantial attention  whole conservation frameworks have been built around quantifying levels of site usage in terms of the number of individuals at a site (e.g., the Western Hemisphere Shorebird Reserve Network; WHSRN 1990). What has remained largely unstudied, however, is the actual structure of stopover sites, such as the configuration of habitats that maximizes an individuals ability to rest and refuel while stopped over (Linscott and Senner 2021). Recent work with Whimbrel (Numenius phaeopus) along the Atlantic Flyway, for example, suggests that the distribution of nocturnal roost sites may impose severe limitations on the network of potential stopover sites that can be used (Sanders et al. 2021, Watts et al. 2021). Likewise, species that use ephemeral environments may be forced to commute long distances between foraging areas that are only available for short periods of time, constraining where and when they choose to stop (Pedler et al. 2017). In combination, site conservation efforts must consider the full range of habitats used by species while stopped over. This project focuses on studying the fall migrations of shorebirds in a species-specific and a comparative context to maximize our ability to develop conservation and management objectives that work for a diverse array of species. Specifically, we will place satellite tracking devices on eight species of medium-sized shorebirds about which we have relatively limited information on their migratory patterns (c.f., Lamarre et al. 2021). These species include Short- (Limnodromus griseus) and Long-billed (L. scolopaceus) Dowitchers, American (Pluvialis dominica) and Pacific (P. fulva) Golden-Plovers, Lesser (Tringa flavipes) and Greater (T. melanoleuca) Yellowlegs, and Upland Sandpiper (Bartramia longicauda).","citation":{"date":[{"date":"2020-10-01T00:00:00.000Z","dateType":"start"}],"title":"Alaska Department of Defense
